/public/docs/wizard/treasure
====================
 
/* Updated by Rodney - 9/20/94 */
 
**************************************************************************
IMPORTANT!  THIS RULE IS LAW!!!
**************************************************************************
If you make a magic item that does ANYTHING except for very minor things
THIS COUNTS AS YOUR 1 ITEM PER 100 ROOMS LIMIT!!!!!  You are only allowed
1 item per 100 QUALITY coded rooms.  I.E.,  this means only one exceptional
OBJECT per 100 rooms, not 1 weapon + 1 armour + 1 whatever per 100 rooms.
Also items like this MUST use make_unique_object to ensure that only 1 of
these items will be in the game at any one time.
***************************************************************************
    VERY IMPORTANT ADDITION!!  DATE : 9/20/94  THIS TAKES EFFECT NOW!!
***************************************************************************
 
The shops in town are all in the process of changing.  We now have an
inheritable shop, and they are type-specific, and they will soon be
material-specific as well.  These accept bitfield arguments, just like the
set_new_type() on weapons.  For example:
 
set_treasure_type(TYP_MAP|TYP_MAGIC);
 
The following are the legal treasure types (yes, you must include the "TYP_"):
 
TYP_BOOK     TYP_FURNITURE  TYP_GEM     TYP_JEWELRY   TYP_STATUE  TYP_GLASS
TYP_MEAT     TYP_DRINK      TYP_FOOD    TYP_CLOTHING  TYP_ART     TYP_CONTAINER
TYP_SCROLL   TYP_TABLET     TYP_MAP     TYP_BONES     TYP_TRASH   TYP_MAGIC
TYP_TRINKET  TYP_LIGHT      TYP_POTION  TYP_INSTRUMENT
 
TYP_ALLTREASURES
 
This last sets your treasure object to all treasure types.
 
Now...On with the other functions...
 
I never saw the point of making doc files that did not use all of the
possible functions callable in stuff like armour/weapons in the doc file
itself.  If it's a doc file, then it's supposed to help you, right?
Not to mention that LPmud 2.4.5's docs are not the greatest in explaining
things.  So, I took the time to re-write them.  Here is the documentation
for treasure.
 
--------------------
 
The first lines in any treasure object should be:
 
#include <mudlib.h>
#include <treasure.h>
#include <material.h>
inherit TREASURE;
 
    These lines set up the object to be a treasure object and will
    allow calls to the treasure master object as defined below.
    Also, in the reset function, you should include the following
    line:
if(!is_clone(this_object())) return;
    before calling ::reset(arg).  This is a memory-saving measure.
    The only time when you should not include this line is when
    the treasure needs to reference the master object for some
    reason.
 
--------------------
 
set_name("name");
 
    string name.  Adds the name passed in to the id list.
 
set_alias("alias");
 
    string alias.  This is another name for the object.  It doesn't
    appear anywhere, but it can be used by the player.
 
set_alt_name("alt_name");
 
    string alt_name.  This is yet another name for the object.  It doesn't
    appear anywhere, but it can be used by the player.
 
set_short("short");
 
    string short.  This is the description seen in the player's
    inventory plus a ".\n"
    Sets the short description of the object to short and the long
    description to "You see nothing special.\n"
 
set_long("long.\n");
 
    string long.  Sets the long description of the object to long.
    I added the ".\n" in the LPC line above to remind you that you
    should add the period and newline in the long description
    because LPC doesn't add it in for you.  This is what the player
    will see when they look at the object.
 
set_weight(weight);
 
    integer weight.  This is the weight of the object.
 
set_value(value);
 
    integer value.  This is the selling value of the object.  The
    buyback value is twice this value.
 
set_treasure_type(TYPE1|TYPE2|...);
 
    bitfield TYPE1, TYPE2, ....
 
set_material(TYPE1|TYPE2|...);
 
    bitfield TYPE1, TYPE2, ....
 
set_read("read.\n");
 
    string read.  This is what the player will see if they read the
    object.  I added the ".\n" in the LPC line above to remind you
    that you should add the period and newline in the long description
    because LPC doesn't add it in for you.
 
set_info("info.\n");
 
    string info.  This will be displayed to the owner of the
    treasure if he identifies the it.  I believe there are plans
    here for something like an identify scroll or possibly an
    identify spell for one of the guilds, and this info would be
    displayed to the player at that time.  This is a good place
    to put special information about the treasure.  Usually, a
    hint of the weight is given, as well as if the treasure
    has any special uses.
 
set_no_buy(n);
 
    status n.  Set this to 0 if you want people to be able to
    buy and sell this to and from the store.  Set to 1 if you
    don't.  If you dont set this command, it will default to
    buyable.
 
void set_no_sell(int iX);

Pass a 1 as the parameter to have it be refused in stores. Note that this
works a bit differently from no_buy, in that the more times you call
set_no_sell(1), the more times you then have to call set_no_sell(0) to
get it to a sellable state again. This is done so that the creator can
set it no_sell, and if a guild uses no_sell to prohibit players from selling
checked-out/borrowed items, when the guild calls set_no_sell(0) when the
object is done being borrowed, the item will still not be sellable.

int query_no_sell(); 

Returns sellable status.

set_steal(n)
 
    status n. Set to 1 if you want to make the item unstealable
    by thieves.  Don't abuse this command!  It is meant only for
    things like quest items or objects great importance.  If you
    don't add this command, item defaults to stealable
 
------------------
 
Here is a sample treasure for you to look at:
 
#include <mudlib.h>
#include <treasure.h>
inherit TREASURE;
 
void reset(int iArg) {
  if(!is_clone(this_object())) return;
  ::reset(iArg);
  if(iArg) return;
  set_id("rodney-hayden");
  set_alias("key");
  set_short("glowing key");
  set_long("\
This key is completely black.  However, it also emits a strange blue glow.\n");
  set_value(565);
  set_weight(1);
  set_light(1);
  set_treasure_type(TYP_GEM);
}
